Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

The main objection is that the ladvise ioctl, llapi_ladvise() call, and RPC should all allow multiple advices on a single file at one time. Even if "lfs ladvise" cannot set multiple advices on a single file at once, this will be useful in the future for applications, libraries, and even readahead inside the kernel. One way to implement this is to have a header before the array that describes how many advices are in it so that only a single data structure is passed to the ioctl and RPC:

 struct ladvice_hdr {
        __u32   lah_magic;      /* LADVICE_MAGIC */
        __u32   lah_count;      /* number of entries in lah_advice*/
        __u64   lah_padding[3]; /* unused */
        struct ladvice lah_advice[0];
 };

This also needs a man page. Please create a SEPARATE lfs-ladvise.1 man page that describes the usage, arguments (units, that end and length cannot be used at the same time (error or one overrides the other?))and reference it from the main lfs.1 page under SEE ALSO.  The next patch should describe the "willneed" parameter.

Patch Set 13: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

You seem to have missed my comment on the last review:

The main objection is that the ladvise ioctl, llapi_ladvise() call, and RPC should all allow multiple advices on a single file at one time. Even if "lfs ladvise" cannot set multiple advices on a single file at once, this will be useful in the future for applications, libraries, and even readahead inside the kernel. One way to implement this is to have a header before the array that describes how many advices are in it so that only a single data structure is passed to the ioctl and RPC:

 struct ladvice_hdr {
        __u32 lah_magic; /* LADVICE_MAGIC */
        __u32 lah_count; /* number of entries in lah_advice*/
        __u64 lah_padding[3]; /* unused */
        struct lu_ladvise lah_advise[0];
 };

That the current "lfs" command and CLIO stack cannot handle multiple advices at one time doesn't bother me (llapi_ladvise() can return an error for lah_count > 1 for now, though of course it would be better if it actually worked).  What I don't want is to change the userspace API or the network protocol to add this in the future.

This also needs a man page. Please create a SEPARATE lfs-ladvise.1 man page (not part of lfs.1, see http://review.whamcloud.com/13478 for example.) that describes the usage, arguments (units, that end and length cannot be used at the same time if they do not match) and reference it from the main lfs.1 page under SEE ALSO. The next patch should describe the "willneed" parameter in the lfs-ladvise.1 man page.
